*TP3 weapon profile:*
- Emad: 20 of 22 waves (91%) — the backbone
- Ghadr: 21 of 22 waves (95%) — paired with Emad
- Shahed-136: 7 of 22 waves (32%) — supplementary role
- Advanced systems introduced late (Fattah W11, Sejjil W12, Kheibar Shekan W20--21)

*TP4 weapon profile:*
- Shahed-136: 15 of 18 waves (83%) — now the backbone
- Emad: 2 of 18 waves (11%) — dramatically reduced
- Ghadr: 3 of 18 waves (17%) — dramatically reduced
- Cruise missiles: 3 of 18 waves (17%) — *new category entirely*
- Kheibar Shekan: 1 of 18 waves (6%)

== The Drone Pivot: Why?

The shift from ballistic-dominant (TP3) to drone-dominant (TP4) likely reflects several factors:

+ *Cost-exchange ratio:* A Shahed-136 costs \$20,000--50,000. An Arrow-3 interceptor costs \$2--3 million. Forcing defenders to expend premium interceptors on cheap drones is a deliberate attrition strategy. In TP3, Israel reportedly consumed a significant portion of its Arrow inventory.

+ *Production capacity:* Iran can manufacture Shahed-136 drones at industrial scale. Ballistic missile production is slower and more resource-intensive. After TP3 consumed 550+ ballistic missiles, Iran may have faced inventory constraints.

+ *Multi-theater demands:* TP4 targets 12 countries simultaneously. Drones are more suitable for distributed, lower-priority targets (Gulf shipping lanes, Omani ports) while reserving ballistic missiles for hardened Israeli targets.

+ *Lessons from Ukraine:* Russia's sustained Shahed campaigns against Ukraine demonstrated that drone saturation degrades air defense networks over time, even when individual drones are intercepted.

